c (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Hugh Arbuthnot was born about 1265, in Morayshire, Scotland as the son of Arbuthnot and ?. He married Lady Arbuthnot about 1295, in Morayshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1265–":"umbes 1265–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","1296–Female":"1296–Surnud","1234–Male":"1234–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1269":"1269","1234":"1234","1265":"1265","1296":"1296","about 1265":"umbes 1265","about 1295":"umbes 1295","about 1296":"umbes 1296","Morayshire, Scotland":"Morayshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1265–":"noin 1265–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1269–Female":"1269–Kuollut","1296–Female":"1296–Kuollut","1234–Male":"1234–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1269":"1269","1234":"1234","1265":"1265","1296":"1296","about 1265":"noin 1265","about 1295":"noin 1295","about 1296":"noin 1296","Morayshire, Scotland":"Morayshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1265–":"environ 1265–Décédé","1265–Male":"1265–Déc